oviet, or council gives Russia its official name, UNION OF SOVIET SOCIALIST REPUBLICS.›     Russia's Armed Forces are of the largest in the world. Russia has estimated that they have over 3 million people in them. Military service begins at the age of 18 and has to last at least two years.›     Russia's land is of huge grassy plains, thick forests, high moutains, and rugged plateaus. One-third of Russia is covered with forests and Russia has one-fifth of the world's timber. Russia's plant life mostly consists of mosses, small plants, and low shrubs. Animal life ranges from deer and elk to leopards and hyenas.›     Russia's economy is mostly based on mining and agriculture and its total production ranks second only to that of the United States.›     Russia has a very bitter cold climate and more than half of the country is covered with snow for over six months a year. This is mainly due to the fact that a large part of Russia is located north of the Arctic Circle.›     Russia's people are very numerous and so are their backgrounds. The average Russian gets a formal education. If one does well he or she will go on to special schools or trade schools and they will have a specified career for the rest of their lives. If one does poorly in school he or she will be forced to discontinue his or her education. ›     All in all Russia aint to bad except for its way of government.    